data.content:
MSTest has a built-in `CollectionAssert` class and better assertion methods. Your current approach using `Assert.IsTrue` loses meaningful failure messages.

Here's the improved version:

```csharp
[TestMethod]
public void GetActiveUsers_ReturnsOnlyActiveUsers()
{
    var service = new UserService();
    var users = service.GetActiveUsers();

    // Use AreEqual for exact counts — shows expected vs actual on failure
    Assert.AreEqual(3, users.Count);

    // Use IsTrue with a message, or CollectionAssert for collection-level checks
    Assert.IsTrue(users.All(u => u.IsActive), "Expected all users to be active");

    // Use IsNotNull instead of != null
    var admin = users.SingleOrDefault(u => u.Role == "Admin");
    Assert.IsNotNull(admin, "Expected an Admin user in results");
}
```

**Key improvements:**

| Instead of | Use | Why |
|---|---|---|
| `Assert.IsTrue(x.Count > 0)` | `Assert.AreEqual(3, count)` | You already check `== 3`, so `> 0` is redundant |
| `Assert.IsTrue(a == b)` | `Assert.AreEqual(a, b)` | Failure shows *expected vs actual* values |
| `Assert.IsTrue(x != null)` | `Assert.IsNotNull(x)` | Clearer intent and failure message |
| `Single()` (throws) | `SingleOrDefault()` + `IsNotNull` | Gives an assertion failure, not an exception |

**Other `CollectionAssert` methods worth knowing:**

```csharp
CollectionAssert.Contains(users, expectedUser);
CollectionAssert.AllItemsAreNotNull(users);
CollectionAssert.AllItemsAreUnique(users);
CollectionAssert.AreEquivalent(expected, actual); // same items, any order
CollectionAssert.AreEqual(expected, actual);      // same items, same order
```

The general rule: pick the most specific assertion available — it produces the most helpful failure messages.
